BioMerieux, Michelin, Schneider: French Equity Market Preview

-- B y   M a r t h e   F o u r c a d e   a n d   M a t t h e w   C a m p b e l l
-- 
2011-04-26T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-25/biomerieux-michelin-schneider-french-equity-market-preview.html
The following stocks may be active
in  France . Symbols are in parentheses after company names and
prices are from the previous close.  France’s CAC 40 Index rose 0.4 percent to 4,021.88. The SBF
120 Index rose 0.42 percent to 3,015.64 in Paris.  BioMerieux (BIM)  SA: The maker of tests for HIV and
hepatitis said it aims for sales growth of 5 percent to 6
percent this year. The shares dropped 0.8 percent to 73.29
euros.  European Aeronautic, Defence & Space Co. (EAD FP): Airbus
SAS made bigger savings than forecast under its ‘Power 8’
recovery plan,  Les Echos  reported, citing an interview with
Chief Operating Officer Fabrice Bregier. The planemaker has
booked 2.5 billion euros in net savings, compared with the
planned 2.2 billion euros, and has 10 billion euros of extra
cash, against the 5 billion euros forecast. The shares  L’Oreal SA (OR)  : The world’s largest cosmetics-maker’s
Chief Executive Officer Jean-Paul Agon earned 12 percent more
last year as the world’s largest cosmetics maker boosted
profitability after declines in 2008 and 2009. Agon’s total
remuneration for 2010 climbed to 3.8 million euros from 3.4
million euros a year earlier. The shares retreated 0.2 percent
to 85.68 euros.  Michelin & Cie. (ML FP): The world’s second-largest
tiremaker said first-quarter revenue rose 28 percent, led by
surging demand for specialty tires to equip construction
equipment and agricultural vehicles. The stock showed little
change at 63.70 euros.  Renault SA (RNO)  : French carmakers Renault SA and PSA
Peugeot Citroen will finish paying back the 6 billion euros they
borrowed from the country’s government earlier than expected,
Industry Minister Eric Besson said. The shares added 1.3 percent
to 38.40 euros.  Schneider Electric SA (SU)  : The world’s biggest maker of
low-and medium-voltage equipment said shareholders approved a
plan for a two-for-one stock split, scheduled to take place
after June 30, at its annual meeting. The stock rose 2.7 percent
to 117.3 euros.  Valeo SA (FR)  : France’s second-biggest auto-parts maker
said first-quarter sales rose 15.6 percent to 2.67 billion euros
on recovering demand from automakers. A 19.2 percent gain in
sales to carmakers led the advance. Valeo gained 0.6 percent to
41.69 euros.  Vranken-Pommery Monopole (VRAP FP): The champagne maker
said first-quarter sales rose 6 percent to 57.7 million euros.
The shares fell 1 percent to 35.10 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
